---
title: "TurboQuant"
abstract: >
  TurboQuant (arXiv:2504.19874) is a recent compression algorithm that shrinks the memory
  behind LLM attention and vector search several-fold: vectors stored at a few bits per
  coordinate, no retraining, provably near-optimal error. This article rebuilds its one-bit
  core and shows why the design is subtle — the obvious compressor, rounding every
  coordinate to its nearest level, is *optimal* for reconstruction yet quietly scales every
  dot product by 2/π. Watch the bias appear in a histogram, then build the sketch that
  removes it on the same bit budget.
tags: [research, capstone]
---
use math   // pi, sqrt, sign, round, cos, sin
use vec

```md
**The library.** A search engine's "understanding" of a sentence is an *embedding*: an
arrow in d-dimensional space. Similar meanings point in similar directions, and the number
behind every search result is a dot product — large when a stored vector and a query agree,
zero when they are unrelated. Here is one stored vector: a simple ramp, scaled to length 1
so scores stay comparable.
```

d = input::int(min: 8, max: 40, step: 4, default: 20, label: "dimension d")
x = normalize(1 + iota(d))

```md
**The query.** Instead of fixing one query, put it on a dial: the query y is a unit vector
sitting at an angle θ from x. Both arrows have length 1, so the true score is exactly cos θ
— 1 at 0°, 0 at 90°, negative beyond. Whatever compression does to x, this is the number
it must preserve, at *every* angle.
```

angle = input::real(min: 0, max: 180, step: 5, default: 40, label: "query angle θ (degrees)")
theta = angle * pi / 180
true_ip = cos(theta)
```latex
y^\top x = \cos\theta = ${round(true_ip, 4)}
```

```md
**One bit, naively.** The budget is brutal: each stored number becomes a single bit, so
each coordinate must round to one of just two values, ±0.7979/√d (where those levels come
from in a moment). Feed the ramp in coordinate by coordinate and look at what comes out:
every coordinate of x points up, so every one of the d bits says *up* — the output is a
flat line. The whole shape of the vector is gone, and no rescaling brings it back.
```

levels = [-0.7979, 0.7979] / sqrt(d)
naive_copy = quantize(x, levels)
plot::line(x, naive_copy)

```md
**The spin.** The fix for wasted bits is a *random rotation* Π: spin the whole space before
rounding (and remember Π, so you can spin back). Rotation changes no length and no dot
product — it only scrambles coordinates — but after it, no coordinate is special: Πx is
simply a random direction, equally likely to point anywhere. So model exactly that — a
random unit vector — and magnify one coordinate by √d: a standard bell curve. *That* is why
the two levels sit at ±0.7979/√d — they are the best possible pair for a Gaussian (the
Lloyd–Max codebook), and what they keep of each coordinate is its sign.
```

g ~[d] rand::normal(0, 1)
spun_x = normalize(g)
one_coordinate = sqrt(d) * spun_x[0]
plot::histogram(one_coordinate)

```md
**Rounding, done right.** Snap every rotated coordinate to its nearest level and measure
what the compressed copy gets wrong. The average squared reconstruction error lands next to
the paper's one-bit table — rotate, round, and you have the *best possible* one-bit
reconstruction:
```

snapped = quantize(spun_x, levels)
d_mse = E(normsq(spun_x - snapped))
```latex
D_{\text{mse}},\ b = 1 \;=\; E\,\lVert x - \hat{x} \rVert^2 = ${d_mse} \qquad (\text{paper: } 0.36)
```

```md
**The catch.** Now score the query against the compressed vector. The query rides through
the same rotation (rotations preserve the angle θ), and the histogram of its score should
pile up around the true answer ${round(true_ip, 3)}. It piles up short — at 2/π of it.
Drag θ anywhere: the shortfall follows the score, always the same fraction.
```

g2 ~[d] rand::normal(0, 1)
sideways = normalize(g2 - (g2 @ spun_x) * spun_x)
spun_y = cos(theta) * spun_x + sin(theta) * sideways
rounded_score = spun_y @ snapped
plot::histogram(rounded_score)
mean_rounded = E(rounded_score)
```latex
E[\,y^\top \hat{x}\,] = ${mean_rounded} \qquad \tfrac{2}{\pi}\, y^\top x = ${round(2 / pi * true_ip, 4)} \qquad \big(y^\top x = ${round(true_ip, 4)}\big)
```

```md
**Why 2/π, exactly.** A sign remembers a Gaussian's direction but forgets its size: for
z ~ Normal(0, 1), E[z · sign(z)] = E|z| = √(2/π) ≈ 0.798. Rounding pays that factor once
because each kept coordinate agrees with the true one only in direction — and once more
because the codebook level 0.7979 *is* √(2/π), chosen to minimize *reconstruction* error
with no regard for dot products. The two factors multiply to exactly 2/π, independent of d,
of the query, of everything. And no amount of averaging repairs a shifted mean: the
estimator is *biased*.
```

```md
**The fix — sketch, don't round.** TurboQuant spends the same bits differently. Instead of
rounding x's own coordinates, project x onto m random directions and store one sign each —
*was the projection up or down?* — plus x's length as one ordinary float. To score a query,
read each stored sign against the query's own projection onto the same direction: add it
when the bit said up, subtract when it said down, rescale by √(π/2) — precisely the size the
signs forgot. Geometry keeps the estimate honest, because the query's projections are tied
to x's by exactly cos θ. At m = d this stores the same bit budget rounding used. (In the
paper this sketch, QJL, compresses the *residual* of a multi-bit first stage; at a one-bit
budget that stage stores nothing and the residual is x itself.)
```

m = input::int(min: 1, max: 128, default: 20, label: "sketch size m (bits stored)")
// Projections of two fixed unit vectors onto one random Gaussian direction are correlated
// Gaussians — correlation cos θ. Noise draws those pairs directly; no d×m matrix needed.
onto_x ~[m] rand::normal(0, 1)
unrelated ~[m] rand::normal(0, 1)
onto_y = cos(theta) * onto_x + sin(theta) * unrelated
stored_bits = sign(onto_x)
sketch_score = sqrt(pi / 2) / m * (onto_y @ stored_bits)

```md
**Centered.** Same one-bit hardware, and the histogram now sits *on* the true score. Drag θ
and it follows; drag m and it tightens without ever drifting off. The spread is the price of
one-bit compression — the position no longer is.
```

plot::histogram(sketch_score)
mean_sketch = E(sketch_score)
sketch_err = E((sketch_score - true_ip) ^ 2)
```latex
E[\widehat{y^\top x}] = ${mean_sketch} \qquad \big(y^\top x = ${round(true_ip, 4)}\big)
\qquad E\big[(\widehat{y^\top x} - y^\top x)^2\big] = ${sketch_err} \;\le\; \tfrac{\pi}{2m} = ${round(pi / 2 / m, 4)}
```

```md
**Every query at once.** The dial tested one direction at a time; a real index is asked
about directions it has never seen. So throw queries from *random* directions at the same
compressed bits, and plot estimated score against true score. The rounded copy answers
every question on a line of slope 2/π — systematically short, never recovering. The sketch
scatters wider, but its cloud is centered on the diagonal: right on average, for every
question.
```

probe ~[d] rand::normal(0, 1)
any_query = normalize(probe)
true_score = any_query @ spun_x
rounded_of_query = any_query @ snapped
query_noise ~[m] rand::normal(0, 1)
onto_query = true_score * onto_x + sqrt(1 - true_score ^ 2) * query_noise
sketch_of_query = sqrt(pi / 2) / m * (onto_query @ stored_bits)
plot::scatter(true_score, rounded_of_query)
plot::scatter(true_score, sketch_of_query)

```md
**Buying precision.** The bias was fixable by cleverness; the spread must be bought with
bits. Double the sketch and the squared error halves — the 1/m law, with the paper's
guarantee π/(2m) riding just above it:
```

bit_counts = [5, 10, 20, 40, 80]
sketch_errs = [for mm in bit_counts {
  proj_x ~[mm] rand::normal(0, 1)
  fresh ~[mm] rand::normal(0, 1)
  proj_y = cos(theta) * proj_x + sin(theta) * fresh
  E((sqrt(pi / 2) / mm * (proj_y @ sign(proj_x)) - true_ip) ^ 2)
}]
plot::line(bit_counts, sketch_errs)

```md
**The verdict.** Rounding to the nearest level is the *best possible* one-bit compressor
for rebuilding a vector — and a systematically dishonest one for scoring it. With the dial
at θ = ${angle}°, rounding returns ${mean_rounded} for a true score of
${round(true_ip, 3)}; the sketch returns ${mean_sketch} from the same number of bits. That
unbiased sketch is the estimator riding inside TurboQuant's residual stage — the design
that lets it compress the memory behind LLM attention and vector search several-fold with
no systematic error to propagate downstream.
```
```latex
E[\,y^\top \hat{x}_{\text{mse}}\,] = \tfrac{2}{\pi}\, y^\top x \qquad
E[\,\widehat{y^\top x}_{\text{qjl}}\,] = y^\top x \qquad
E\big[(\widehat{y^\top x} - y^\top x)^2\big] \le \tfrac{\pi}{2m}
```
